<paragraph blockId="12.[143,241,168,192]" box="[143,241,168,192]" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574">
<emphasis box="[143,241,168,192]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[143,1103,207,327]" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574">
The specimen can be easily distinguished from the other two 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[834,941,208,231]" class="Insecta" family="Dictyopharidae" genus="Metaurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,941,208,231]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574">Metaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the distinctly longer cephalic process in front of eyes, longer than length from curved point to posterior margin of eyes, with the ratio about 1.4: 
<quantity box="[748,791,271,295]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="12" pageNumber="2574" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
lateral view. Unfortunately, its abdomen was missing so that the specific status is unknown.
</paragraph>
